 be hurt as much\nas 15 per cent by the new tariff\nbill, according to an analysis sub\nmitted to the Baltimore Associa\ntion of Commerce by G. Harry\nPouder, head of the import and\nexport bureau. But at that, this\ncity will not be hit nearly as hard\nas most others, Mr. Pouder finds\nThis is because 70 per cent of\nBaltimore imports are on the free\nlist and are, therefore, not af\nfected by the tariff law.\nSome few industries, he pointed\nout, will be benefited by the new\nduties. Among these are canned\ngoods, straw hats, toys, furniture,\nchina and glassware. \u201cAmong the\nIndustries unfavorably affected,\u201d\nthe statement says, \u201care sugar\nand a wide diversification of gen\neral importers ranging from de\npartment stores to seed industries.\nIf the foreign sales of merchan\ndise decline, the outbound busi\nness of this port will also, as is\nvividly illustrated in figures for\nthe first five months of 1930.\u201d\nDuring these five months the\ntotal export business of the coun\ntry dropped $450,000,000 from last\nyear\u2019s level. That caused Balti\nmore to do almost $13,000,000\nless export business than it did\nin the same period of 1929.\n\u201cThis decline is largely attrib\nutable to unsatisfactory economic\nconditions at home and abroad\nand perhaps in small part to hesi\ntancy brought about by the pend\ning tariff bill,\u201d Mr. Pouder said.\nW. B. HIBBS CO.\nThe ONLY New York Stock Exchange House\nHaving Its Main Office in Washington\nM EMBER S\nNew York Stock Exchange\nBoston Stock Exchange\nPhiladelphia Stock Exchange\nWashington Stock Exchange\nNew York Cotton Exchange\nChicago Board of Trade\nAmerican Bankers Association\nDistrict Bankers Association\nHIBBS BUILDING\nNational 0540 WASHINGTON, D. C.\nGAS CONCLAVE\nIS PLANNED\nDevelopment of natural gaa\nhaving reached such enormous\nproportions in a comparatively\nshort time, discussion of that\nsubject promises to be one of\nthe notable features of the\ntwelfth annual convention and\nexhibition of the American Gas\nAssociation at Atlantic City, N.\nJ., October 13 to 17. according to\nannouncement made by associa\ntion headquarters in New York.\nAt both the general sessions\nand sectional meetings all of the\nmany problems wh|yh present\nthemselves to the industry will be\ndiscussed by men who are be\nlieved to be the best qualified\nfor this purpose through their\ntraining and experience.\nThe steady growth of the gas\nindustry, both in natural gas en\nterprises and manufactured gas\nproduction and distribution to\nday, is front-page copy for the\nnation\u2019s dally press. Not only\nthe newspapers, but the trade\npapers, including many outside\nof the gas industry, as well as a\nlarge number of popular maga\nzines have devoted much space to\nthe fact that the oldest of the\nutilities have expanded phenom\nenally.\nWhile natural gas topics will\nplay a prominent part in the pro\nceedings, as a whole, the conven\ntion this year will have a strong\nsales slant. Prominent men and\nwomen have been Invited to\nspeak on merchandising from\nvarious angles\u2014industrial sales,\nas well as domestic sales.\nWhile details of the convention\nprogram are not available, the\nmembers of the general program\ncommittee are busily engaged in\nputting it into shape.\n25","height":"30426","width":"24221"}}
